column1: Will legislation amending or repealing Section 230 of the Communications Act of 1934 become law before 1 October 2022?
column6: ['Business', 'Technology', 'Society', 'US Politics', 'US Policy']
with the time frame coming to an end, no progress or news has come out regarding this and the signs shows that nothing will

I think that there is no chance of this happening before October 1: Considering that October 1 is only one day away and there hasn't been huge momentum in amending or repealing this act. I think there will be more headlines once this issue starts to gain more of a following, but until then I don't think that this law will be repealed or amended in the next 24 hours. However, I do predict that this act will become more popular in the coming year because social media is becoming more popular and there are more new users.

I believe there is little to basically no chance of this happening. Recently, there have been no major concerns about social media postings, and no recent/prior action has been held to amend this. I believe in later times this may be changed, but not now regarding the current status of our nation.
Well,... no.

No shot. No bill in Congress right now regarding 230 has gained noteworthy momentum that would make me suspect that 230 would be repealed by October 1. This was a hot topic last year about this time, but it appears to have been a political fad that gained no actual traction in Congress.
its almost time
Timeline is too short term for anything to be passed
No chance
There is a decent chance this might happen, however there to pass an amendment to this law before October is a tall act for a slow bureaucracy.

While it is likely such legislation will be passed given the outcry against social media companies for allowing controversial posts, it is highly unlikely that this will be completed by October 1. There have been no recent major developments regarding this to indicate a change by the date.
Truly doubt this will happen by October 1
Even less likely now that time has passed
I am giving this a 0% chance since there is not enough time for anything to pass amending or repealing Section 230 of the Communications Act of 1934 before October 1st 2022.

There is no way any kind of legislation could pass in time. It does not seem like anything is even being seriously considered, let alone voted on, revised, or approved by the president. I looked at recent and upcoming congressional activities, and did not see any mention of relevant legislation, and the news, even tech focused news, does not have any recent stories about this besides one article from 9/12 about a comment from Biden. Basically everything I found that thought an alteration was plausible was from 2021. There is no way something will happen before 10/1/22.

There is no chance that this can happen in the next two weeks. WIth the way the Senate works, Senators and their aides would have to do a lot of research, a bill would have to be drafted and read through, and then a vote would have to take place. Also, voting in the Senate, or in the government more generally takes place in policy windows. This policy window is not open right now because there are other things that people are focused on, specifically elections.
Adjusting for time

I realized I should probably have this at 0% instead of 1%. There isn't time for anything to pass the Senate. The White House issued a principles statement the other day that mentioned Section 230, but that's about it.
Unlikely in the time remaining, due to the way the US Senate works.

I'm using the US Constitution and another well-known bill as reference classes. The Constitution in particular has been amended 27 times in 2 and a half centuries and the other only 9 times in 1 and a half centuries. In simplest philosophy, it takes time for amendments to occur to well-established and popular/infamous laws.

Any such change would be fought over so much that I doubt a successful vote could be reached in this time frame. In addition to Republicans, Manchin and/or Sinema would probably block anything most Democrats would want to do, and Democrats would likely block any substantial change pushed by Republicans because they would disagree with its substance. And so any proposal would be filibustered and would die. If the filibuster were eliminated and/or some giant new issue emerged, that could potentially change things, although Manchin and/or Sinema would still likely block any Democratic proposal; I'll give it a 5% chance.

I see no means by which the Republican opposition to Section 230 on the grounds that it improperly enables cancel culture/censorship can be squared with the Democratic opposition to Section 230 on the grounds that it doesn't sufficiently push against hate speech/misinformation, and thus no means to reach 60 votes in the Senate in the next eleven months.
